##The hospital-sense of 1716 medical and nursing staff during the war

Wechat Bqshenyidu

Features, Beijing Youth Daily, the official public number

Reporters Lan Zimu, Han Qian, Li Jianan intern reporters Zhou Manqing, long Tianyin

Editor / Yang Baolu & Song Jianhua

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The hospital admissions department is training doctors to wear protective clothing correctly

"Hospital Sense Department" , full name "hospital infection management department" . As the name suggests, its main task is to carry out effective prevention and control of hospital infection.

In this attack of new pneumonia, how to carry out "hospital sense prevention and control" is also facing an unprecedented test. According to the official report, as of 2400 hours on 11 February, a total of 1,716 confirmed cases, including six deaths, had been reported by medical personnel throughout the country. Of these, 1,502 cases were reported in Hubei Province and 1,102 in Wuhan, accounting for 73.4% of the confirmed cases among health care workers in Hubei Province.

After the outbreak of the epidemic, a third-class hospital sense department doctors revealed that now around the daily sense control work has basically "stopped, " in full response to the epidemic at the same time, is trying to "make up lessons. ".

In a number of medical rescue teams to Wuhan, have set up a full-time hospital sense prevention and control personnel, they told Beiqingshen once reporters, "do not let every member of the team infection, is the meaning of our existence. "

The hospital infection dates back to early January

Infection among health care workers can be traced as far back as early January.

According to internal statistics released on Feb. 3,36 people are suspected to have been infected at Tongji Hospital, a hospital affiliated to the Tongji Medical College. Several doctors confirmed to the deep at one time, the epidemic early due to a lack of awareness, January 20, the medical staff concentrated on the case of infection, now very few people infected. As of February 11, Tongji Hospital staff confirmed infection of more than 40 people, belonging to the Wuhan Hospital Chinese medicine staff infection less hospital.

According to Emergency Physician Lu Jun of Tongji Hospital, in the emergency department, the medical staff usually wore masks for general medical purposes. They knew at the time that there might be patients with fever of unknown origin, so they raised the level, start Wearing N95 masks. But at the time, medical staff did not know that the virus could be transmitted from person to person, was so sensitive that protection was not mentioned at the highest level, and was not wearing protective clothing or goggles.

Tongji hospital surgeon Zhang Ming also confirmed to a reporter that in early January when the hospital staff medical examination, only some people wear masks.

On January 10 or earlier, Yu Changping, deputy director of the Department of Respiratory Medicine at Wuhan University People's Hospital, as a member of the epidemic prevention and control expert group, began consulting fever patients suspected of pneumonia of unknown origin in the hospital, at that time, the hospital has set up a ward for such patients. "CT scans of the lungs in these patients show clear viral pneumonia symptoms, mostly double lung lesions, which are rare and can be seen five or six times a day, " he said

Yu Changping, who was also infected soon afterwards, told reporters that the symptoms of this new coronary pneumonia were easy to ignore at the initial stage, "before SARS and bird flu, it was common to have a high fever and a severe cough, but my symptoms were fever and the temperature was not very high, " Yu even heard his colleagues tell him, in some cases, the CT scan of the lungs was negative for viral pneumonia, while in others it was just a sore throat. The CT scan of the lungs was normal, but the nucleic acid test was positive.

Since January 14, Yu Changping has developed fever, with a high fever of about 38 degrees. He did not take it seriously until the 17th, before the Department dinner, in order to prevent the impact of colleagues, only to do a lung CT, the results showed that the bilateral lung edge of the existence of light ground-glass floc lesions, "I specialize in this, one can see that I was infected. " That day, Yu Changping and another department colleagues are in hospital isolation.

On the third day of Hospitalization, Yu began to get sicker and developed symptoms of chest tightness and wheezing. His condition was most serious around January 23, when he developed dyspnea, "He was given oxygen through a nasal catheter and his oxygen flow reached 5-6 liters per minute. He could only lie in bed and could not move. " It was only after January 24 that Yu's symptoms of dyspnea slowly subsided.

Yu Changping believes that new coronary pneumonia is a self-limited disease, "just get through the 'tug of war' with the virus, and things will get better. The purpose of oxygen therapy and drug therapy is to help patients get through the dangerous period and maintain the stability of body function, mainly depending on their physical quality and recovery ability."

But not all doctors have the same physique and luck. On Feb. 7, Li Wenliang, an ophthalmologist at Wuhan Central Hospital, died at the age of 34. On Feb. 10, tongji Hospital Organ Transplant Professor Colin Zhengbin also died of new pneumonia.

On February 14, a press conference was held to report 1,716 confirmed cases by medical staff

"human-to-human transmission" ignored at the beginning of the epidemic

From the start, Yu thought the pneumonia of unknown origin was likely to be transmitted from person to person. Of the patients he treated, only one worked in the south China Seafood Market, and the rest had no history of contact, "Our hospital was in Wuchang and the south China Seafood Market was in Hankou. The patients were from different places and there was no clustering, so there was probably human-to-human transmission. "

Even so, because the government did not issue a report of human-to-human transmission at the time, Yu did not take adequate precautions and wore only a surgical mask. "At the time, I was alert, but I did not pay special attention, " he said.

And only 1 km away from the South China Seafood Market, Wuhan Central Hospital Back Lake area, was the first to be affected. After the Lake Hospital district Doctor Xu Jie told the deep once reporters, "there (south China Seafood Market) once there is a problem, the first will be sent to us here, early is our hospital admission of more pneumonia patients. "

Xu Jie told reporters in the deep once, in the Central Hospital after the Lake Hospital district has also become a designated hospital for fever patients, has increased six or seven medical wards, each ward about 30 beds. Xu said that the new beds were mainly for the treatment of hospital staff infected.

On January 3, after Dr. Li Wenliang was admonished, Xu Jie's department gave an oral notice not to talk about pneumonia. As the hospital was close to the south China Seafood Market, many people came to inquire about Xu Jie's specific situation. "I was still busy 'refuting rumors' everywhere, so everyone should not be alarmed. This thing has not been confirmed to be SARS, and we need to wait for an official announcement. "

Xu says he also noticed an increase in medical visits to the inhalation unit. It turned out that one of the dining-room doors was facing the medical department, and that one was closed, so we had to go around to the other door. Around January 15, he recalled, as more patients came in, health care workers were told to start wearing surgical masks. "there was a merger of gastroenterology and Ophthalmology, and the gastroenterology ward was set aside for this kind of patient. "

Xu's department does not receive fever patients, but a director of the department developed fever around February 10 and was transferred to the hospital for intubation treatment. Two other doctors were also infected.

A number of central hospital doctors to the Shenzhen once reporter said that the current central hospital actual or suspected infection of new pneumonia in more than 150 people. Most of the large-scale infections among health care workers occurred without the knowledge of many people in the early stages, or before the official announcement of human-to-human transmission.

Tongji hospital surgeon Zhang Ming told deep once, according to his understanding, at first, because of breathing, endocrine and ICU Department of Staff Infection, the hospital began to tense up.

Zhang Ming, after New Year's Day, the hospital began to remind doctors to do a good job of protection, found that fever patients to pay attention, many doctors are aware of the possible risk of infection. Since then, surgeons have also begun wearing masks during rounds, until mid-january, really pay attention, but wearing masks are not all surgical masks. Without adequate protection, at least six or seven of the surgeons he knew had been diagnosed with the infection.

At that time, the hospital was in a "tight inside, tight outside" state, the medical staff know to do a good job of protection, but the patient did not know. Fever patients and other patients have gathered, the spread of infection, health care workers in a large number of contacts with patients and their families in the process of infection probability is also increased.

Zhao Jianping, director of the Department of respiratory and critical care in Tongji Hospital, reported that from the beginning of January to 20, key departments such as the infection department, Emergency Department and Respiratory Department in Tongji Hospital had better protection, and the protection status at that time was the same as it is now, the number of infected persons in infection department, Emergency Department and aspiration department was very low, but the number of infected persons in Surgery Department and Examination Department was higher.

Heavily armed medics

Problems needing attention in hospital sense prevention and control mechanism

Under the pressure of increasing the infection rate of medical staff, the problems that hospital-sense prevention and control system should pay attention to are also exposed.

At the end of January, a support Hubei medical team arrived in Wuhan and went to the designated aid hospital for docking. Meeting for the first time, the two sides on the isolation ward on the transformation of differences.

"three-zone two-access is a minimum requirement for a respiratory infectious disease ward. "

In accordance with the design of the assisted hospital, the entire inpatient department building has been converted into an isolation ward, divided into three sections: contamination zone, cleaning zone and buffer zone. However, according to the current design, medical staff in the removal of protective equipment, but also need to return to the contaminated area again before leaving. This was opposed by more than medical team experts and hospital sense group members. Shen Cheng, the hospital sense group of the medical team, said the so-called "three zones" refers to the clean area, buffer zone, pollution area independent division, "two channels" refers to the isolation ward from two separate channels through, can not take the "back road.

At the docking site, the director of the assisted hospital although expressed the special period of transformation difficulties, but in the same night again on the ward transformation. Although still unable to reach the "two channels" , but through the addition of walls, through the wall and other means, finally reached the medical staff off the protective equipment, do not need to return to the contaminated area.

For such a phenomenon, as the provincial capital city of the third-class hospital feeling doctor Qin Ming is not unfamiliar. Qin Ming told reporters that apart from special infectious disease hospitals, most hospitals do not have the original conditions to treat patients with infectious diseases. The "three-zone-two-channel" design will greatly reduce the size of hospital wards, "but if there is no such design, will undoubtedly increase the risk of hospital infection

Shen Cheng, a hospital-sense doctor in Wuhan, said that after his medical team arrived in Wuhan, the hospital-sense Group was the first to put into work in the department, under great pressure. "That's why we're here, to keep everyone from getting infected and to go home safely. "

Qin Ming told reporters that in an ideal world, every 200 to 250 patients would be accompanied by a full time hospital staff, whose work would include daily inspections of clinical department operations and monitoring of fever and infection in the ward, and follow-up of discharged patients. "But many general hospitals don't have that kind of configuration. "

This ideal state of protection for health care workers is difficult to achieve when there is a shortage of staff. At the end of January, Zhang Ming, who had been in surgery, was assigned to the fever clinic at Tongji Hospital headquarters. He told the reporter that the fever clinic has 15 people on three shifts every day, taking on more than 1,000 patients every day. Starting from the end of January, eight people on a shift are taking on about 800 patients every day, and he has to see 40 patients a day. After the shelter was built, coupled with the closure of the community, now, the number of patients dropped a lot, but still about 300 people a day.

Xu Jie was transferred to Nanjing Road Hospital district emergency surgery sitting. Is Responsible for the surgical diagnosis patient carries on the preliminary examination, also has some fevers patient, needs to carry on the body temperature examination, pats the lung Ct.. "Some of the surgeons in the Nanjing Road Hospital area have been infected, some may be exposed and are still under quarantine, and there are not enough hands at the moment. Medical staff in plastic surgery, obstetrics and gynecology, ophthalmology and dermatology are all moving forward. "

In principle, if a health care worker is infected, anyone who comes into contact with him should be quarantined. But Xu said the current conditions did not allow, "if this standard isolation, hospitals will have to shut down, no one to work. "

Some of the hospitals have sent out requests for help

The protective materials are in short supply under the attack of epidemic situation

Deep once through a number of doctors in Wuhan to fight new pneumonia front-line understanding, at present, the family's protective materials are still in a relatively tense state.

A staff member in charge of material donation at the People's Hospital of Wuhan University told us that at one time, the hospital was in short supply of disposable protective products such as face masks and protective clothing. Under the circumstances of government distribution, social donations and purchases with funds, to ensure that the first-line fever clinics and wards of the health care workers protection needs, but the stock has been able to maintain only two or three days of consumption.

Xu said the current quality of Protective Materials "varies from day to day. ". "Some of the suits are probably second-class, some are industrial; there are Spanish, German and unbranded. You don't even know where it's from. You wear what you're given. It's not optional. We are still an emergency department, and we give priority to medical care, so the situation in other departments is even more predictable."

Cai Yi, the head of the pain department at the People's Hospital, is currently in charge of treating patients in a ward at Houhu hospital. He said that because of the shortage of protective clothing, has begun to control the number of rounds into the contaminated area of medical staff, "can only be we stay inside a little longer, reduce the consumption of protective clothing. "

Qin Ming told reporters that for medical N95 masks, face screens, protective clothing and other high-level protective supplies storage, funding has become a difficult issue around. The Health Commission in some areas has earmarked funds for hospitals to buy protective equipment, but policies vary from place to place, "without this money, the reserves would be even smaller, " said Qin Ming's city, in the previous two years, they had allocated a special fund of about 200,000, and with some of that money, they bought 3,000 medical N95 masks. After the outbreak, Qin Ming had inventory of his hospital supplies, "If the same is a serious situation, tight bar can use a month. "

He hopes that in the future, the cost of protective supplies can be covered by the disease control department, which has the financial support, or by an agreement with equipment suppliers to form a "rotating" mechanism, "For example, I have 20,000 N95 masks in stock, and when they are about to expire, I can move them to an infectious disease hospital where they are in greater demand. "

The doctor practiced wearing protective clothing in pairs

Calls for a unified regulatory process

Qin Ming described routine sensory control work around the world has now basically "stalled" and efforts are being made to "catch up" as well as responding fully to the outbreak.

Once officially on the front line, Shen's medical team demanded that everyone treat their peers as potential "suspected cases. ".

In isolation, the potential risks are not limited to the layout of the wards. Everything is upside down, from the direction of the patient's communication, to the posture of the infusion, and sensory control permeates every detail. Shen Cheng and other members of the hospital sense team also check the body temperature of all team members every day, three times in the morning, middle and evening to the ward, supervise the operation process of all people. They have found that nurses routinely remove the outermost protective gloves after injecting patients.

In Wuhan, an aid medical team is about to train local medical staff on how to put on and off protective clothing. To get everyone's attention, the demonstrator starts by saying, "this is what we need to survive. " But after the training begins, the presenter soon disagreed with the members of the sense group over the order in which he wore the hat and mask.

"You go to every medical team and there are probably dozens of different versions of the order in which you take off your protective clothing, " Qin Ming said, explaining that after the outbreak, many experts recommended wearing masks before hats, but in practice, some female health workers have long hair and risk slipping off if they wear a mask first.

Equally divisive is the manner in which masks are removed. It is now common practice to avoid touching hands when removing a mask, but when Qin Ming went to a medical company for training, he was specifically advised to hold the mask with one hand, "Some people who are not skilled in the operation may cause the mask to rebound, the danger is even greater. "

"compared with the standard of clinical practice, there is no uniform requirement on the protection of hospital sense, from the HHC to the HA to hospitals, " Qin Ming said, adding that the differences in details reflected the need for urgent improvement. Different brands of protective equipment operate in different ways, he once wanted to work with experts to develop a unified regulatory process, "but this job is really difficult. "

Behind the mechanism, the human factor is more obvious.

The greater challenge, Qin Ming says, is awareness, "especially among older health care workers, who may be paralyzed by too much experience. "

In Qin Ming's view, the department was established on a large scale. Between 1990 and 1995, "in some places it was a retirement department for medical staff who were too old to work the night shift. "

Even now, the college's talent pool is not ideal. Qin Ming said that in the medical title system, there is no single sequence of hospital admissions and there is not much room for advancement, which leads many people to be reluctant to study related subjects.

Qin Ming, who specializes in public health, says the first thing the CDC needs to improve is its personnel. If someone with clinical experience enters the prevention field, the improvement of professional ability will surely bring the high efficiency of hospital sense prevention and control.

In the midst of a sudden outbreak, it seems difficult for the medical staff to remain unscathed. Almost every major epidemic makes a big difference in infection control and disease prevention, Qin Ming said, "but hopefully not at such a huge cost every time. "

(with the exception of Yu Changping, Lu Jun and Cai Yi, all the interviewees were living under pseudonyms.)
